oviding an innovative vantage point from which to reconsider the material culture of medieval marriage. Setting these twin effigies alongside wedding rings and dresses as the agents of matrimonial ritual and embodied symbolism, the author presents the "double tomb" as far more than mere romantic sentiment. Rather, it reveals the careful artifice beneath their seductive emotional surfaces: the artistic, religious, political and legal agendas underlying the medieval rhetoric of married love. Dr JESSICA BARKER is a Lecturer in Medieval Art at the Courtauld Institute of Art, London. Published with the generous financial assistance of the Henry Moore Foundation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMarriage in art. 0aSepulchral monuments, MedievalzEurope. 0aSepulchral monuments, MedievalzGreat Britain. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aART / Subjects & Themes / Religious.2bisacsh  aAlice Chaucer.  aAnne of Bohemia.  aCanterbury Cathedral.  aEngland.  aJohn of Gaunt.  aJoão I, King of Portugal.  aMargaret Holland, duchess of Clarence.  aPhilippa of Lancaster, Queen of Portugal.  aPortugal.  aRichard II.  aWestminster Abbey.  achurch interiors.  acommemorating the dead.  aecclesiastical material culture.  afuneral effigies.  agender.  amomento mori.  amonastery of Batalha.  astone effigies.  athe body.  atomb decoration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446922?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446922/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles